When a small group of living things (a small population) separates itself from the main population from which it originates (for example, if they cross a mountain range or a river, or if they go or leave a new island, so that they cannot return), they are often found in a different place from the one they, or are in a different place from the former.
This new environment has different resources and different competition, so the new population will need different characteristics or adaptations to be a stronger competitor than it needed to be until that time.
The original population has changed nothing change; they still need; they need for the same adaptations as before.
As time goes of time, when the new population begins to adapt to its new surroundings, it also starts to look less and less like the rest of the population.
Eventually, after billions or even millions of years, the two populations will have such a different appearance that the same species cannot be considered.
This process is called speciation, which simply means the formation of new species.
