Technological determinism is a term encompassing a wide range of ideas in practice, from the technological impetus or technological imperative to a strict sense that human nature of thesis, is driven by a logic underlying logic associated with science and its manifestation in technology.
Many interpretations of technological determinism share two main ideas: that the development of technology itself follows a path that goes beyond cultural or political influence and that technology has "effects" in societies that are inherent, more than socially conditioned.
For example, one could say that motor cars forcefully lead to the development of roads.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for a lot of cars, so the new production methods are designed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
The property of mass vehicles also generates a higher incidence of accidents on roads, which leads to the invention of new techniques in healthcare to repair of injured bodies.
